Media notes: This woodpecker's namesake feature is actually visible in the photo. 95% of the time this plumage cannot be seen in the field.  The bird given this name because if you shoot one and pick it up, the small red patch is readily apparent, and that’s one way ornithologists invented bird names. Other examples include Ring-necked Duck, Rough-winged Swallow, and Sharp-shinned Hawk - all named for features that can only be seen in the hand after shooting the bird.

Observation Details: M & 2 Fl dad fed each one Both FlS made an attempt at the feeder but ended up back on the tree trunk to be fed. M returned to the feeder, and 1 FL flew over the feeder, but he went back to the tree. F on feedee then flew off NW. Fl followed. At 11:45, an M came to the feeder while the FL clung the trunk of the favorite tree. He went back and forth, feeding the baby 15 times in a row. I've never seen anything like it. Normally, they stay for up to 3 or 4 feedings in a row. Baby got scared off by a squirrel, and the M returned to the tree to find the baby gone. He flew off NW, and the baby came back insight and followed the dad. The dad came back several more times and would fly NW each time with a mouth full of chipped sunflower seeds. Dad was very careful at picking out the chipped seeds and avoided the whole black sunflower seeds.

I think I witnessed the parents finding the fledgling not long after he fledged. When I arrived the nesting cavity entrance had no head peaking out as it had several days prior. I saw the mother fly up to the nesting cavity with food and put her head in and out of the nesting cavity but emerge with food still in her beak. There was a lot of vocalizing after that. After several minutes I was standing at the trellis near the big stone planter in the rose garden and I heard a loud noise overhead. The father and fledgling flew overhead with the father practically on top of the young one. The father then moved up to a tree leaving fledgling at the base of the planter. The fledgling slowly made his way up the side of the planter to the top. Both parents were close by vocalizing. The fledgling then flew to the lower part of the nesting tree.  The fledgling started slowly making his way up the side of the tree. That's when the mother arrived with food and fed the youngster.  Exciting!

Continuing male first reported by Twila Watkins on November 5. Black and white barred back, central tail feathers white with black barring, some black speckling on white rump, red crown and nape, slightly buff-tinted belly and sides of face. First refound today by Danny Tipton at 10th & Main where he showed it to us. The bird later moved around the neighborhood where we saw it at two other locations, most notably at the east end of nearby Portales City Park. We also observed it poking out of a suspected roosting cavity at approx. 2:10 p.m. in the park. It called on a number of occasions, both during flight and while perched. It responded to playback of RBWO calls by poking its head out of the cavity. Photos.

Lots of red-bellied woodpeckers about.  The 5 that I observed, all male, visited the suet station, perched on pine tree brances and nearby trees, moving to and fro. Visiting the mixed bird seed station, too. Sharing the suet staion at one point with a red-winged blackbird (each were on opposite sides of the suet cages. These woodpeckers moving up/down the mature pine teee, too--foraging, as well as flying among the poinciana and oak trees, always revisiting the feeder.   I sat for this observation period, this morning, which lasted approx. 1/2 hour, distanced about 25-45' from the foraging birds; used a zoom lens to capture some of the observed birds. Observing a driveway island "garden" area, that is about 30-feet in diameter, an old, mounded dirt and plants island surrounded by brick. This island "garden" contains one very mature pine tree, about a dozen or more agave plants, about a dozen split leaf philodendron, an invasive species brazillian pepper (shrub), and ground vines... with feeders hanging above from one of the pine branches--this feeding station contains mixed seed and a suet house.

Media notes: phantom of the opera
Observation Details: some unusual poses (photos below) that we later learned was "sunning" caught our attention  the site Naturally Curious described a RBWO that did the exact same thing we witnessed: "flattened itself on the branch with its body facing the sun and then fanned its wings out while cocking its head, raising its crown feathers, opening its beak and appearing to look at the sun.  This behavior is common enough to have a name – the woodpecker was “sunning” itself.  While preening, stretching and calling often takes place intermittently while the bird is engaged in sunning, it may also enter a stupor or state of lethargy."
